00:03:12.570 --> 00:03:15.830
So, first business example.

00:03:15.830 --> 00:03:19.540
You&#39;ve got an executive, and
do you demote, or

00:03:19.540 --> 00:03:21.660
do you fire him?

00:03:21.660 --> 00:03:24.900
And this comes from an actual
conversation, an actual real

00:03:24.900 --> 00:03:28.340
life situation that I was
working on with a CEO.

00:03:28.340 --> 00:03:30.619
And so, the basic situation
was this.

00:03:31.950 --> 00:03:35.340
He had a great executive, or
like an executive who,

00:03:35.340 --> 00:03:36.320
just a great effort.

00:03:36.320 --> 00:03:38.470
Like, he hired him.

00:03:38.470 --> 00:03:41.530
He was working harder than
anybody else in the company,

00:03:41.530 --> 00:03:43.580
doing you know, like,
everything he was supposed to.

00:03:43.580 --> 00:03:45.470
Everybody liked him, because
he worked so hard, and

00:03:45.470 --> 00:03:47.070
like was a general smart
person.

00:03:49.180 --> 00:03:51.450
But he was just in over his
head knowledge wise.

00:03:51.450 --> 00:03:56.680
He did not have the knowledge
and the skills to basically do

00:03:56.680 --> 00:03:58.320
what the company needed him to
do or,

00:03:58.320 --> 00:04:00.580
like, really compete against
the competition, so

00:04:00.580 --> 00:04:02.040
he couldn&#39;t actually keep him
in the job.

00:04:02.040 --> 00:04:04.110
But he&#39;s a great guy.

00:04:04.110 --> 00:04:08.910
And you know, so the question
is, well.

00:04:08.910 --> 00:04:10.810
Should I fire this person?

00:04:10.810 --> 00:04:13.670
Or can I just move him into a
lower role and

00:04:13.670 --> 00:04:15.160
bring in a person above him.

00:04:15.160 --> 00:04:17.640
And then, like, you know, that
would be real cool.

00:04:17.640 --> 00:04:20.720
So, let&#39;s look at how you
kind of make that decision.

00:04:21.880 --> 00:04:24.310
So you in this, in this case
this was the CEO, so

00:04:24.310 --> 00:04:25.080
you as a CEO.

00:04:25.080 --> 00:04:28.760
So, one like, look, it&#39;s
really hard if somebody comes

00:04:28.760 --> 00:04:30.930
to work everyday like at, you
know, 6 a.m.,

00:04:30.930 --> 00:04:32.446
and is like working till 10
p.m.

00:04:32.446 --> 00:04:33.980
And like doing it,

00:04:33.980 --> 00:04:36.370
like, harder than anybody in
the company.

00:04:36.370 --> 00:04:38.590
It&#39;s really hard to just say,
well, sorry, like,

00:04:38.590 --> 00:04:40.670
nice effort, but you don&#39;t get
an A for an effort.

00:04:40.670 --> 00:04:42.140
You get an F because I fired
you.

00:04:47.055 --> 00:04:48.860
&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt; Nobody nobody wants to

00:04:48.860 --> 00:04:49.740
have that conversation.

00:04:51.555 --> 00:04:52.660
&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt; And then, a demotion is

00:04:52.660 --> 00:04:54.750
kind of neat because from the
CEO&#39;s point of view, and this

00:04:54.750 --> 00:04:56.730
is, he&#39;s like, Look, like, we
can keep him in the company.

00:04:56.730 --> 00:04:57.590
He works so hard.

00:04:57.590 --> 00:04:58.620
He&#39;s a good example of

00:04:58.620 --> 00:04:59.920
somebody who gives a great
effort.

00:05:01.300 --> 00:05:03.970
And you know, like, and then
he&#39;s got a lot of

00:05:03.970 --> 00:05:05.730
friends in the company, and
they&#39;re, you know,

00:05:05.730 --> 00:05:07.980
from a cultural standpoint
like, it&#39;s a, it&#39;s a win,

00:05:07.980 --> 00:05:10.838
win because like, he gets to
stay and, and, you know,

00:05:10.838 --> 00:05:13.500
like and then I can bring in
somebody that can solve my

00:05:13.500 --> 00:05:16.240
problem, but I, I don&#39;t have
to create another problem.

00:05:18.250 --> 00:05:19.280
And then if you think about it

00:05:19.280 --> 00:05:22.180
from the executive&#39;s
perspective,.

00:05:22.180 --> 00:05:24.390
And what they would think,
it&#39;s like, well, I,

00:05:24.390 --> 00:05:26.000
you know, I don&#39;t want to be
demoted.

00:05:26.000 --> 00:05:27.490
But I really don&#39;t want to be
fired,

00:05:27.490 --> 00:05:30.850
because if I get fired that&#39;s
a way harder more complicated

00:05:30.850 --> 00:05:34.290
thing to explain to my next
employer than I got demoted.

00:05:34.290 --> 00:05:35.510
Like, getting demoted is like,

00:05:35.510 --> 00:05:37.280
well, I didn&#39;t really get
demoted, I got a new job.

00:05:39.053 --> 00:05:40.619
&gt;&gt; A smaller title.

00:05:40.619 --> 00:05:44.329
And then, you know, the, the,
the last thing is it enables,

00:05:44.329 --> 00:05:47.829
you know, like theoretically,
while, like, you know,

00:05:47.829 --> 00:05:50.990
the company, you know, we
value all our employees.

00:05:50.990 --> 00:05:51.770
We brought you in.

00:05:51.770 --> 00:05:53.700
We made a commitment to you as
an employee.

00:05:53.700 --> 00:05:54.980
And, like, we value everybody.

00:05:54.980 --> 00:05:55.530
And it kind of

00:05:55.530 --> 00:05:57.210
will enable you to keep
growing with the company.

00:05:57.210 --> 00:05:58.680
And so.

00:05:58.680 --> 00:06:00.790
You know and this was the kind
of initial conversation I

00:06:00.790 --> 00:06:01.850
had with a CEO and, and

00:06:01.850 --> 00:06:04.430
I said well wait a minute, I
said, let me ask you this.

00:06:04.430 --> 00:06:05.800
Like what is the,

00:06:07.090 --> 00:06:09.350
what&#39;s the equity package that
this exec has?

00:06:09.350 --> 00:06:10.650
And he goes well what do you
mean?

00:06:10.650 --> 00:06:11.200
And I was like,

00:06:11.200 --> 00:06:15.480
well like does he have like,
director level compensation,

00:06:15.480 --> 00:06:18.070
does he got like a vice
president level compensation?

00:06:18.070 --> 00:06:20.020
Does he have a point and a
half?

00:06:20.020 --> 00:06:21.220
Does he have 0.4% or what?

00:06:22.790 --> 00:06:23.640
and, you know?

00:06:23.640 --> 00:06:25.860
That kind of gave the CEO
pause.

00:06:25.860 --> 00:06:29.200
He&#39;s, like, well, he does have
a point and a half.

00:06:29.200 --> 00:06:30.770
And I was, like, okay.

00:06:30.770 --> 00:06:32.490
So you&#39;re an engineer in your
company.

00:06:34.050 --> 00:06:38.280
How do you feel about somebody
who used to be the head of

00:06:38.280 --> 00:06:40.680
sales, who got brought in with
a point and a half.

00:06:40.680 --> 00:06:41.790
Now, mind you, you&#39;re an
engin-,

00:06:41.790 --> 00:06:42.950
what do your engineers get?

00:06:42.950 --> 00:06:43.572
Like, they get.

00:06:43.572 --> 00:06:46.510
.1%, .2%, what are they
getting at this point?

00:06:48.070 --> 00:06:50.200
So how are they going to feel
about somebody who&#39;s

00:06:50.200 --> 00:06:53.340
not the head of sales with
1.5% of the company.

00:06:53.340 --> 00:06:55.490
And he was like oh.

00:06:57.240 --> 00:06:59.890
And I was like, yeah, oh.

00:06:59.890 --> 00:07:01.369
Because like how fair is that?

00:07:02.380 --> 00:07:04.590
So are you going to take the
equity away, are you up for

00:07:04.590 --> 00:07:06.180
doing that, are you up for
going back and

00:07:06.180 --> 00:07:08.300
taking back his compensation?

00:07:08.300 --> 00:07:09.410
And like how productive do

00:07:09.410 --> 00:07:11.710
you think he&#39;ll be if you take
away his compensation?

00:07:12.932 --> 00:07:16.620
And then secondly, like Will
people give him

00:07:16.620 --> 00:07:20.051
the same respect now that
you&#39;ve demoted him,

00:07:20.051 --> 00:07:23.767
because they knew him as this,
and now he&#39;s this.

00:07:23.767 --> 00:07:27.121
And so like, I knew you when
you were head of sales,

00:07:27.121 --> 00:07:29.695
now you&#39;re the regional
manager, and

00:07:29.695 --> 00:07:32.349
you&#39;re telling me what the to
do?

00:07:32.349 --> 00:07:34.650
You&#39;re telling me I need to
make that call?

00:07:34.650 --> 00:07:37.310
Like, seems to me you got
demoted.

00:07:37.310 --> 00:07:39.070
You know, who are you to talk
to me?

00:07:39.070 --> 00:07:39.890
I&#39;m an up and comer.

00:07:39.890 --> 00:07:41.930
I&#39;ll be the next VP of sales
at the next company.

00:07:43.030 --> 00:07:45.530
So all these things come into
play.

00:07:45.530 --> 00:07:47.580
And so when you look out at
the end,

00:07:47.580 --> 00:07:50.780
like you may think you&#39;re
dealing with one person.

00:07:50.780 --> 00:07:55.510
You may think that this is a
demotion, or a firing of one

00:07:55.510 --> 00:07:57.720
person, and what does it mean
according to that one person.

00:07:57.720 --> 00:07:59.980
But what you&#39;re really doing
is you&#39;re saying look.

00:07:59.980 --> 00:08:01.660
What does it mean to fail on
the job?

00:08:01.660 --> 00:08:02.800
Particularly, a very,

00:08:02.800 --> 00:08:06.130
the highest paid, highest
compensated job

00:08:06.130 --> 00:08:08.550
in the company from an equity
standpoint, and then,

00:08:08.550 --> 00:08:10.200
like, what&#39;s required to
maintain your equity?

00:08:11.320 --> 00:08:13.660
Like is it good enough to put
in an effort?

00:08:13.660 --> 00:08:14.650
Or do you have to get a
result.

00:08:15.810 --> 00:08:18.420
And in different situations at
different levels, look,

00:08:18.420 --> 00:08:20.340
these answers will come out
differently.

00:08:20.340 --> 00:08:21.800
And if this had been a person
not that

00:08:21.800 --> 00:08:23.690
was an executive brought in
from the outside but

00:08:23.690 --> 00:08:25.670
was somebody who you maybe
promoted past where they

00:08:25.670 --> 00:08:28.400
should have been, and didn&#39;t
ever get that equity, like,

00:08:28.400 --> 00:08:30.140
maybe you make a different
decision.

00:08:30.140 --> 00:08:32.550
But you&#39;ve gotta understand
what it&#39;s going to mean to

00:08:32.550 --> 00:08:35.080
everybody, not just the person
you&#39;re talking to.

00:08:36.100 --> 00:08:36.680
Example two.

00:08:36.680 --> 00:08:39.190
An excellent employee asks for
a raise.

00:08:39.190 --> 00:08:40.600
Good employee.

00:08:40.600 --> 00:08:42.750
This isn&#39;t like a, like the
last employee.

00:08:42.750 --> 00:08:44.930
This is like really good
employee.

00:08:44.930 --> 00:08:47.570
So excellent employee asks for
a raise.

00:08:47.570 --> 00:08:49.490
So, look.

00:08:49.490 --> 00:08:50.760
Your first thing is like,

00:08:50.760 --> 00:08:52.760
they&#39;re really good, they
asked me for

00:08:52.760 --> 00:08:55.910
a raise, they didn&#39;t ask me
for no reason.

00:08:55.910 --> 00:08:58.320
They ask me because they think
they deserve it.

00:08:58.320 --> 00:08:59.070
I want to retain them.

00:09:00.220 --> 00:09:02.020
Like, I want to be fair.

00:09:02.020 --> 00:09:02.980
They&#39;ve done a great job.

00:09:02.980 --> 00:09:07.430
I want to be fair, and, like,
you know,

00:09:07.430 --> 00:09:09.900
I know that if I give them
this raise, like,

00:09:09.900 --> 00:09:12.280
it&#39;s going to be all love
coming my way,.

00:09:12.280 --> 00:09:14.945
That&#39;s going to be if I gave
you a raise, we&#39;re good,

00:09:14.945 --> 00:09:16.470
you know, like we&#39;re boys.

00:09:18.450 --> 00:09:19.320
&gt;&gt; Look at you.

00:09:19.320 --> 00:09:19.849
You got a raise.

00:09:20.970 --> 00:09:22.650
&gt;&gt; It&#39;s awesome.

00:09:22.650 --> 00:09:24.870
So like, you know from your
perspective you know what you

00:09:24.870 --> 00:09:27.200
want to do when somebody asks
you for a raise.

00:09:27.200 --> 00:09:29.880
And then if you look at it,
okay, so

00:09:29.880 --> 00:09:33.470
what about from their
perspective, what,

00:09:33.470 --> 00:09:35.850
how would they, like, take it
if you gave them the raise.

00:09:35.850 --> 00:09:38.020
And now you have to remember
the employee from, for

00:09:38.020 --> 00:09:41.400
them to get to the point where
they&#39;ve asked you for a raise.

00:09:41.400 --> 00:09:43.620
This is not something they
just like woke up one

00:09:43.620 --> 00:09:45.940
morning and like, I&#39;m going in
and asking for a raise, right?

00:09:45.940 --> 00:09:48.363
Like this is something where
they&#39;ve thought about it

00:09:48.363 --> 00:09:50.996
a lot, they&#39;ve you know,
compared their other options,

00:09:50.996 --> 00:09:53.472
they may have an offer from
another company, you know,

00:09:53.472 --> 00:09:55.895
they&#39;re, it&#39;s something their
spouse probably has

00:09:55.895 --> 00:09:57.181
been talking to them about.

00:09:57.181 --> 00:09:59.470
And so it&#39;s a serious thing.

00:09:59.470 --> 00:10:01.530
And so, if you give it to
them,

00:10:01.530 --> 00:10:03.370
they&#39;re very likely to feel
very good about it.

00:10:03.370 --> 00:10:04.770
Like, they may be like
paranoid,

00:10:04.770 --> 00:10:06.200
about like why are you giving
me a raise?

00:10:06.200 --> 00:10:07.141
But, very unlikely.

00:10:07.141 --> 00:10:09.491
Much more and they&#39;ll feel
like.

00:10:34.456 --> 00:10:36.187
I&#39;m sorry, I have to just let
the whole thing play.

00:10:43.099 --> 00:10:44.133
And that&#39;s, that&#39;s for

00:10:44.133 --> 00:10:46.368
those of you who don&#39;t know,
that&#39;s Bobby Shmurda.

